    margin: 10px 0;
    border-radius: 5px;
    line-height: 1.6;"><p>To fix your code, you should ensure that you are using the correct Tcl commands to interact with the Tk theme. It looks like you're trying to use a custom function (<code>set_theme</code>) that does not exist in the standard Tkinter library or Tcl, as the standard Tcl command to change the theme is <code>ttk::style theme use</code>.</p>
<p>Assuming you are using a standard Tkinter setup, and you have a <code>self.master</code> object that represents the top-level Tk widget, you can toggle the theme like this:</p>
<pre><code class="language-python">import tkinter as tk
from tkinter import ttk

def toggle_theme(self):
    current_theme = self.master.tk.call(&quot;ttk::style&quot;, &quot;theme&quot;, &quot;use&quot;)
    if current_theme == &quot;azure-dark&quot;:
        self.master.tk.call(&quot;ttk::setTheme&quot;, &quot;azure&quot;)  # Assuming 'azure' is a valid theme
    else:
        self.master.tk.call(&quot;ttk::setTheme&quot;, &quot;azure-dark&quot;)  # Assuming 'azure-dark' is a valid theme
</code></pre>
<p>Please note the following points:</p>
<ol>
<li>
<p>The <code>ttk::setTheme</code> call assumes that 'azure' and 'azure-dark' are valid themes that you've already installed in your application. If you haven't defined these themes, this call will fail. Ensure that your themes are defined and added to the list of available ttk themes.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>The <code>self.master</code> object should be the root window or another widget that has access to the Tk instance.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>For the above code to work, the custom themes should be properly initialized with their respective style configurations in your application.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Make sure to import the <code>tkinter</code> and <code>tkinter.ttk</code> modules as needed.</p>
</li>
</ol>
<p>Remember that Tkinter's theming can be quite specific. If you are using a custom theme library or handling themes in a non-standard way, you will need to adjust the code to match the API of the library you're using. If "set_theme" is a custom method, you must make sure that it is defined and available to be called with the correct parameters.</p></div>

