    margin: 10px 0;
    border-radius: 5px;
    line-height: 1.6;"><p>To prove this statement, we will need to use a combination of properties and definitions of symmetric positive definite matrices.</p>
<p>First, let's recall the definition of a symmetric positive definite matrix. A matrix A ∈ ℝ^(n×n) is symmetric positive definite if it is symmetric (A = A^T) and for any non-zero vector x ∈ ℝ^n, we have x^T A x &gt; 0.</p>
<p>Now, let's assume that A is a symmetric positive definite matrix and x is a vector such that x^T A x = 0. We aim to prove that x = 0.</p>
<p>Assume, for contradiction, that x is not equal to the zero vector. This means there exists at least one entry in x that is non-zero.</p>
<p>Let's denote the i-th entry of x as x_i. Then, x_i is non-zero for some i.</p>
<p>Now, let's define a new vector y ∈ ℝ^n where all entries are the same as x except for the i-th entry. In other words, y_j = x_j for j ≠ i, and y_i = 0.</p>
<p>Since y is a vector derived from x by modifying only one entry, we can see that y ≠ 0.</p>
<p>Next, let's consider the expression y^T A y.</p>
<p>Using the definition of y, we have:</p>
<p>y^T A y = (x_1, x_2, ..., x_i-1, 0, x_i+1, ..., x_n) A (x_1, x_2, ..., x_i-1, 0, x_i+1, ..., x_n)^T</p>
<p>Expanding this, we get:</p>
<p>y^T A y = x_1^2 + x_2^2 + ... + x_i-1^2 + 0 + x_i+1^2 + ... + x_n^2</p>
<p>Note that each of the terms in the sum is non-negative.</p>
<p>However, since A is symmetric positive definite, we know that for any non-zero vector z, z^T A z &gt; 0.</p>
<p>Applying this to y, we have:</p>
<p>y^T A y &gt; 0</p>
<p>But we previously found that y^T A y = 0.</p>
<p>This is a contradiction since we have derived a contradiction from our initial assumption.</p>
<p>Thus, our assumption that x is not equal to the zero vector must be false.</p>
<p>Therefore, if A is symmetric positive definite and x A x = 0, it follows that x = 0.</p></div>

