    border-radius: 5px;
    line-height: 1.6;"><p>Research in the field of reading has focused on identifying the cognitive skills that facilitate successful reading acquisition. One area of interest in this domain is the relationship between motor-reduced visual perceptual function and reading ability in preschool children. Motor-reduced visual perceptual function refers to the ability to organize and interpret visual information in the absence of movements. In contrast, motor-active visual perception involves the coordination of visual information with motor actions to gain information about the environment. This review aims to explore the literature on the relationship between motor-reduced visual perceptual function and early Chinese reading ability in preschool children.</p>
<p>In a study conducted by Cheng and colleagues (2015), motor-reduced visual perceptual function was found to be a predictor of early Chinese reading ability in preschool children. The study included 223 Chinese-speaking preschool children who were assessed for motor-reduced visual perception, visual-motor integration, visual attention, and phonological awareness skills. Results revealed that motor-reduced visual perceptual function was a significant predictor of early Chinese reading ability, even after controlling for other cognitive and relevant background variables.</p>
<p>Furthermore, research has also explored the relationship between motor-reduced visual perceptual function and Chinese character recognition, which is a critical component of early Chinese reading ability. In a study by Wang and colleagues (2016), 147 Chinese-speaking preschool children were assessed for motor-reduced visual perceptual function, character recognition, and phonological awareness skills. Results revealed that motor-reduced visual perceptual function was significantly correlated with Chinese character recognition, and this relationship was moderated by phonological awareness skills. These findings suggest that motor-reduced visual perceptual function may play a crucial role in Chinese character recognition development and that phonological awareness skills may influence the relationship between motor-reduced visual perceptual function and Chinese character recognition.</p>
