    margin: 10px 0;
    border-radius: 5px;
    line-height: 1.6;"><p>Ash's world was dark and cramped, surrounded by the cold walls of the shipping box. The sound of his own breathing echoed loudly in his ears, his heart pounding with fear and regret.</p>
<p>"Why did I think I could outsmart them? Why did I think I could survive like this?" Ash lamented to himself, feeling the weight of his mistakes settling into his bones.</p>
<p>After what felt like an eternity inside the box, Ash finally felt a jolt and heard the distant sound of paper tearing. Dappled light began filtering through the air holes, and Ash braced himself for the worst. He had no idea what kind of macro had purchased him or what they planned to do with him.</p>
<p>The box was yanked open abruptly, and Ash found himself blinking up into the grinning face of his new owner, a massive anthro rabbit.</p>
<p>"Ah, you look even better in person," the rabbit cooed, his voice sickeningly sweet.</p>
<p>Ash's heart plummeted; no matter how much he wished it were different, his life was now in the hands of the giant creature before him. And by the excited gleam in the rabbit's eyes, it wasn't going to be an easy life.</p>
<p>Over time, Ash adapted to his new surroundings, always on edge beneath the rabbit's watchful gaze. His owner, who was named Carver, used Ash for his own twisted entertainment: sometimes making him perform demeaning acts like juggling or dancing, sometimes seeing how much fear he could instill in the small cheetah, and even one terrifying night, almost swallowing him whole before laughing and spitting him back out.</p>
<p>It hadn't taken Ash long to realize that this was not the life he wanted, and even though he knew the risks, he started to plot his escape. He observed Carver's routine, learned his habits, and found a potential path to freedom through the ventilation system of their home.</p>
<p>Under the darkness of night and with his heart thudding in his chest, Ash put his plan into action. He slipped into the vent system, crawling through the cold metal tunnels until he emerged in the living room. The front door was tantalizingly close, but Carver's enormous form was fast asleep between him and his escape. Holding his breath, Ash crept closer and closer to the door, praying his small feet wouldn't betray him.</p>
<p>Finally, he reached the door and managed to slip through a crack at the bottom. Breathing a sigh of relief, Ash scrambled away from the house, vowing never to return.</p>
<p>His life as a fugitive would be difficult, and danger would always be close at hand, but Ash was determined not to be a victim again. In that moment of freedom, beneath the glow of the moon, he felt a renewed sense of hope and conviction.</p>
<p>No matter who or what threatened him, Ash knew one thing was certain: in this dangerous world of giants, he would continue to fight for his survival.</p></div>

